{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox Christian leader | type = Bishop | name = Most Rev. Richard Henry Ackerman | title = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington|Bishop Emeritus of Covington]] | image = | alt = | caption = | church = [[Roman Catholic Church]] | archdiocese = | diocese = | see = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington]] ([[emeritus]]) | term = May 17, 1960 – November 28, 1978 | predecessor = [[William Theodore Mulloy]] | successor = [[William Anthony Hughes]] <!-- Orders --> | ordination = August 28, 1926 | ordinated_by = | consecration = May 22, 1956 | consecrated_by = | rank = <!-- Personal details --> | birth_date = {{birth date|1903|8|30}} | birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1992|11|18|1903|8|30}} | death_place = [[Covington, Kentucky|Covington]], [[Kentucky]] | previous_post = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of San Diego|Auxiliary Bishop of San Diego]] (1956–1960) }}
'''Richard Henry Ackerman''', [[Holy Ghost Fathers|C.S.Sp.]] (August 30, 1903 – November 18, 1992) was an [[United States|American]] [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. A member of the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]], he served as [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington|Bishop of Covington]] from 1960 to 1978.
==Biography== Richard Ackerman was born in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], to John and Josephine (née Richard) Ackerman.<ref name=curtis>{{cite book |last=Curtis |first=Georgina Pell |title=The American Catholic Who's Who |volume=XIV |year=1961 |publisher=Walter Romig |location=Grosse Pointe, Michigan}}</ref> After graduating from [[Duquesne University]] [[Secondary education in the United States|High School]], he entered the Duquesne University [[Drama school|School of Drama]] in 1920.<ref name=diocese>{{cite news |work=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington]] |title=Most Rev. Richard Henry Ackerman, C.S.Sp., S.T.D. |url=http://www.covingtondiocese.org/index.cfm/NewsItem?ID=86693&From=Home}}</ref> He entered the [[Holy Ghost Fathers|Congregation of the Holy Ghost]] in 1921 and made his [[Profession (religious)|religious profession]] at [[Ridgefield, Connecticut|Ridgefield]], [[Connecticut]] on August 15, 1922.<ref name=diocese /> He was [[Holy Orders|ordained]] to the [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priesthood]] by Bishop [[Maurice F. McAuliffe]] on August 28, 1926.<ref name=hierarchy>{{cite news |work=Catholic-Hierarchy.org |title=Bishop Richard Henry Ackerman |url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/backerman.html}}</ref>
Between 1926 and 1940, Ackerman served as [[master of novices]] for the Holy Ghost Fathers, [[Curate|assistant pastor]] of [http://www.stbenedictthemoor.org/ St. Benedict the Moor Parish] in Pittsburgh, assistant to the National Director of the [[Association of the Holy Childhood|Pontifical Association of the Holy Childhood]], assistant to the [[professor]] of [[philosophy]] at St. Mary Seminary in [[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]], and assistant pastor at [http://www.oldstmarysdetroit.com/index.php St. Mary Parish] in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]].<ref name=diocese /> He was named National Director of the Holy Childhood Association in 1941, and [[Vice president|Vice-President]] of the Association's Superior Council in 1947. Upon the [[Silver Jubilee]] of his priestly ordination in 1951, he was presented with the [[Pro Ecclesia et Pontifice|Grand Cross ''Pro Ecclesia et Pontifice'']] by [[Pope Pius XII]].<ref name=diocese />
On April 6, 1956, Ackerman was appointed [[Auxiliary Bishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of San Diego|San Diego]], [[California]] and [[Titular Bishop]] of ''Lares''.<ref name=hierarchy /> He received his [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|episcopal consecration]] on the following May 22 from [[John Francis Dearden|Bishop John Dearden]], with Bishops [[Jean Gay]], C.S.Sp., and [[Thomas John McDonnell|Thomas McDonnell]] serving as [[Consecrator|co-consecrators]], at [[Cathedral of Saint Paul in Pittsburgh|St. Paul's Cathedral]].<ref name=hierarchy /> He was later named the seventh [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington|Bishop of Covington]], [[Kentucky]] by [[Pope John XXIII]] on April 4, 1960, and installed at the [[Cathedral Basilica of the Assumption, Covington|Cathedral Basilica of the Assumption]] on the following May 17.<ref name=hierarchy /> From 1962 to 1965, he attended the [[Second Vatican Council]], where he was a member of the conservative ''[[Coetus Internationalis Patrum]]''.<ref name=lefebvre>{{cite news |work=The Biography of Marcel Lefebvre, 2004 |title=Members of the Coetus Internationalis Patrum |last=[[Bernard Tissier de Mallerais|Tissier de Mallerais]] |first=[[Bernard Tissier de Mallerais|Bernard]]}}</ref>
Upon reaching the mandatory retirement age of 75, Ackerman resigned as Bishop on November 28, 1978, after 18 years of service.<ref name=hierarchy /> He later died at age 89, and is buried at St. Mary Cemetery in [[Fort Mitchell, Kentucky|Fort Mitchell]].<ref name=diocese />
