'''Satish Chandra Vidyabhusan''' (30 July 1870 - 25 April 1920) was a [[Bengalis|Bengali]] scholar of [[Sanskrit]] and [[Pali language|Pali Language]] and principal of [[Sanskrit college|Sanskrit College]].
==Early life== Satish Chandra Vidyabhusan was born in 1870 in [[Rajbari District]], [[British India]]. His father Pitambar Vidyavagish was a ''Pandit'' and astronomer. In 1888, Satish Chandra passed entrance from Nabadwip Hindu School and in 1892, passed the B.A with Sanskrit Honours from [[Krishnagar Government College]] with gold medal.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Sansad Bangali Charitavidhan (Bengali)|last=Vol - I|first=Subodh C. Sengupta & Anjali Basu|publisher=Sahitya Sansad|year=2002|isbn=81-85626-65-0|location=Kolkata|pages=545}}</ref> He was the first Indian who obtain M.A degree in Pali from [[Calcutta University]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ZlyDot9RyGcC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=Satish+Chandra+Vidyabhusan&source=bl&ots=WCO129M24M&sig=vgAnH3O6kZS3xMG0KjpcGGest2M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ7bLVqufaAhWLKo8KHYaHAvUQ6AEISTAG#v=onepage&q=Satish%20Chandra%20Vidyabhusan&f=false|title=Collected Papers on Buddhist Studies|last=Padmanabh S. Jaini|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caluniv.ac.in/academic/department/Pali.html|title=Department of Pali|last=|first=|date=|website=caluniv.ac.in|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref>
==Career== Vidyabhushan was known for his distinguished knowledge in [[Indian logic]] and [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan Buddhist Text]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=s9xCCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=Satish+Chandra+Vidyabhusan&source=bl&ots=1vv33bP3f4&sig=mJJXeyY2Y7A8NLJ7MFZBazIn3eI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ7bLVqufaAhWLKo8KHYaHAvUQ6AEIRjAF#v=onepage&q=Satish%20Chandra%20Vidyabhusan&f=false|title=Indian Paṇdits Engaged in Tibetan Translations of Buddhist Logic|last=Dr. Mantosh Mandal|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> He, along with [[Sarat Chandra Das]], prepared Tibetan-English dictionary. Vidyabhusan went to [[Sri Lanka]] in 1910 for study and on his return he was appointed the Principal of Sanskrit College, [[Kolkata]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=sVIAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR10&lpg=PR10&dq=Satish+Chandra+Vidyabhusan&source=bl&ots=91ydqCSnLa&sig=F_SqTvKs7v6p1JrsVFatQ41MbPo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAmMH9s-faAhXIMY8KHeULC6A4ChDoAQgrMAM#v=onepage&q=Satish%20Chandra%20Vidyabhusan&f=false|title=Early Buddhist Monachism: 600 BC - 100 BC|last=Sukumar Dutt|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> He became the Assistant editor of the Buddhist Text Society. He edited magazine of [[Bangiya Sahitya Parishad|Bangiya Sahitya Parisad]] for 22 years. Vidyabhushan was a linguist having knowledge in [[Buddhist literature]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[German language|German]] and French language. Vidyabhushan number of books on Buddhist Tibetan culture, logic, Sanskrit and Systems of Indian Philosophy. In 1906 he received the title of ''Mahamahopadhyaya''. and got Ph. D in 1908<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Indian_Biographical_Dictionary_(1915)/Acharji,_Satis_Chandra|title=The Indian Biographical Dictionary (1915)|last=C. Hayavadana Rao|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 21, 2018}}</ref>
