'''Sayyida Shirin''' ({{lang-fa|سیده ملک خاتون}}), also simply known as '''Sayyida''', was a [[Bavandid]] princess, who was the wife of [[Buyid]] ruler of [[Rey, Iran|Ray]], [[Fakhr al-Dawla]]. She was the ''[[de facto]]'' ruler of Ray during the reign of her son, [[Majd al-Dawla]] (r. 997–1029).

== Origins ==
[[File:Caspian coast of Iran during the Iranian intermezzo.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of northern Iran]]
According to the medieval historian [[Hilal al-Sabi']] and the modern historian [[Wilferd Madelung|Madelung]], Sayyida Shirin was the sister of the [[Bavandid]] ruler [[al-Marzuban]].{{sfn|Madelung|1975|p=217}} However, according to the [[Qabus nama|Qabus-nama]] made by the [[Ziyarid]] ruler [[Keikavus]] (who was a neighbor of the Bavandids and of Bavandid descent himself), Sayyida Shirin was the niece of al-Marzuban.{{sfn|Madelung|1975|p=217}} [[Hugh N. Kennedy]] calls her the son of a certain Bavandid ruler (''[[ispahbadh]]'') of [[Tabaristan]] named Sharwin, who may be the Bavandid ruler [[Sharwin III]], who was the brother of al-Marzuban. Sayyida Shirin also had a brother named [[Rustam Dushmanziyar]],{{sfn|Huart|1993|p=667-668}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=244}} whose son [[Muhammad ibn Rustam Dushmanziyar]] became the founder of the [[Kakuyid dynasty]]. 

Although Sayyida is called a [[Kurdish people|Kurd]] in some sources,{{sfn|Meisami|1999|p=200}} she is generally agreed to be from the Bavand dynasty,{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=244}}{{sfn|Madelung|1975|p=217}}{{sfn|Madelung|1984|pp=747-753}} which was then of [[Daylamite]] origin.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=244}} [[Encyclopædia Iranica]] also states that; “it should be remembered that “Kurd” in the sources of the 10th-11th centuries refers to all the transhumants of the [[Zagros]] region including the [[Lors]].”{{sfn|Ch. Bürgel|R. Mottahedeh|1988|pp=265-269}}

== Biography ==
At an unknown date, Sayyida Shirin married Fakhr al-Dawla, and bore him two sons named [[Majd al-Dawla|Abu Taleb Rostam]] and [[Shams al-Dawla|Abu Taher]] in the 990s. Fakhr al-Dawla later died in 997 and was in [[Rey, Iran|Ray]] succeeded by Abu Taleb Rostam, who was given the ''[[laqab]]'' of "Majd al-Dawla". Meanwhile, Abu Taher was given the ''laqab'' of "Shams al-Dawla", and became the ruler of [[Hamadan]]. Since both brothers were in the age of minority, power was assumed by Sayyida. Both sons initially declared themselves independent and assumed the title of [[Shah|Shâhanshâh]], but by 1009 or 1010 at the latest had recognized the authority of their relative [[Baha' al-Dawla]], who controlled [[Fars Province|Fars]] and [[Iraq]], and abandoned the title.

In 1006 or 1007, with the assistance of his ''[[vizier]]'' Abu 'Ali ibn 'Ali, Majd al-Dawla attempted to throw off the regency of Sayyida. Sayyida, however, escaped to the Kurd Abu Najr Badr ibn Hasanuya, and together with Shams al-Dawla they put Ray under siege. After several battles, the city was taken and Majd al-Dawla was captured. He was imprisoned by Sayyida in the fort of Tabarak, while Shams al-Dawla took to power in Ray. After a year, Majd al-Dawla was released and reinstated in Ray; Shams al-Dawla returned to Hamadan. Power continued to be held by his mother. However, Shams al-Dawla later tried to seize Ray from Majd al-Dawla, but was stopped by Sayyida. Sayyida later died in 1028.{{sfn|Bosworth|1975|p=177}}

