{{Infobox Hindu temple | name = Udvada Atash Behram | image = Udwada_atash_behram.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Udvada Atash Behram [[Fire temple]] in Udvada | deity = [[Atash Behram]] | festivals= Salgiri, Bahram roj, Zoroastrian New Year | architecture = | temple_quantity = | monument_quantity= | inscriptions = | year_completed = | creator = | map_type = India Gujarat#India | map_caption = Location in Gujarat | coordinates = {{coord|20|29|15|N|72|52|14|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}} | country = India | state = [[Gujarat]] | locale = [[Udvada]] | elevation_m = | website = |}} The '''Udvada Atash Behram,''' also known as the '''Iran Shah''', "King of Iran", is a temple in [[Udvada]], [[Gujarat]] on the west coast of India. It is one of the eight [[fire temple]]s (holy place of worship) of the [[Zoroastrian religion]] in the country. The [[Atash Bahram]], meaning "Victorious Fire", is one of the oldest fire temples in India, dated to the eight century, and represents the historical cultural and religious links with Iran. The current temple was built in 1742 by Dinshaw Dorabjee Mistry from [[Bombay]]. The temple structure, built spaciously, is well decorated and contains the Dasturji Koyaji Mirza hall and a museum. The main hall of the temple is accessed through a two-stage staircase. The temple attracts [[Zoroastrian]] pilgrims from all parts of India, Pakistan and from around the world.
==Location== The Udvada Atash Behram, also called the Iran Shah,{{Sfn|Rose|2014|p=190}} "King of Iran",{{Sfn|Meri|2005|p=877}} is a fire temple of the [[Zoroastrian religion]]; one of the eight in India. It is located in [[Udvada]] (also spelled Udwada) in [[Gujarat]] on the west coast of India. Outside India, [[Yazd]] in Central Iran has the only other Atash Behram. Udvada, a small coastal village, of about {{Convert|2|km2}} area,<ref name=Sagar>{{Cite news|last=Sagar|first= Homai |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20091004/spectrum/main5.htm|title=Fire of faith |accessdate=10 April 2015|date=4 October 2009|newspaper=The Tribune}}</ref> is on the southern coast of Gujarat. The village was gifted to the priests by the king of [[Mandvi]].<ref name=Mehta>{{Cite web |last=Mehta |first=Behram |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-fire-temple-at-udvada-is-central-to-parsi-religion-1535653 |title=Fire temple at Udvada is central to Parsi religion |date=24 April 2011 |publisher=DNA India}}</ref> It is approachable by road and rail. It is {{Convert|206|km}} away from [[Mumbai]] towards the north, situated between [[Vapi]] town and [[Daman, Daman and Diu|Daman]] on the [[National Highway 8 (India)(old numbering)|National Highway (NH8)]] which passes through Manor. The nearest railway station is also in Udvada which is on the [[Virar railway station|Virar]]-[[Surat railway station|Surat]] section.<ref name=Sagar/>
==History== [[File:Udvada Fire Temple 1905.JPG|right|thumb|[[Udvada]] Atash Bahram in 1905]] Udvada Atash Behram is one of the oldest existing fire temples in India, representing the cultural and religious link with Iran.{{Sfn|Rose|2014|p=190}} The Atash Bahram fire was moved from Iran to India in 715, consequent to the migration of [[Zoroastrians]] in [[Greater Persia]] due to the persecution by the [[Islamic]] rulers who conquered that country; those who moved to India are called [[Parsis]];{{Sfn|Hartz|2009|p=59-60}}{{Sfn|Joshi |2012|p=177}} the earliest link of worship of the sacred fire in Zoroastrian temples is dated to the 4th century BC.{{Sfn|krishnan|2009|p=156}} The Parsis traveled by ship from [[Hormuz Island|Hormuz]] in the [[Persian Gulf]] and landed on the Indian coast at [[Diu, India|Diu]]. They then moved along the coast to [[Sanjan (Gujarat)|Sanjan]], where the local [[Hindu]] king, [[Jadi Rana]], gave them asylum and land to settle down but under a few stipulations.{{Sfn|Hartz|2009|pp=59&ndash;60}}{{Sfn|Joshi |2012|p=177}} They settled down in Sanjan and then established their first Atash Bahram, a first-grade fire temple (fire drawn from sixteen sources) in India in 721 by enshrining the holy fire that had been brought from Iran.{{Sfn|Hartman|1980|p=20}} This temple thus created a ''[[silsila]]'', a traditional link, for the Parsi community of Sanjan with Iran. The consecration ceremony involved long and winding rites, which lasted for many months. The temple flourished, the community took firm roots, and it was their only such temple during that period, though as a community they spread to other regions of India.<ref name= Kotwal>{{Cite web|last=Kotwal|first= Firoze M. |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=4006324&fileId=S0041977X00127557|title=Some observations on the history of the Parsi Dar-i Mihrs|accessdate=10 April 2015|publisher=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies}}</ref> Their stay in Sanjan lasted for about four centuries till political events took a turn. In 1297, the [[Muslim]] ruler, Sultan Mahmud, invaded Gujarat and occupied the Sanjan area also; during this battle the Parsis had sided with the Hindus but it was a lost cause. The Parsis then took shelter in the [[Bahrot caves]] and kept the sacred fire there for 12 years. As the safety conditions improved, the Sanjan priests then shifted, with the holy fire, to another village known as [[Bansda]], and remained there for 14 years, when pilgrims started visiting the fire shrine.{{Sfn|Hartz|2009|pp=59&ndash;60}}<ref name=Iranica>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/iransah|title=Irānšāh|work=Encyclopedia Iranica}}</ref> During this period, one of the pilgrims, Changashah, also known as Changa Asa, of Navsari, who was also a benefactor, who used to travel to Bansda, persuaded the priests of Sanjan to move to Navsari.<ref name=Iranica/>
In 1419, the holy fire was moved by the priests to Navsari, a town near [[Surat]], where they established themselves for more than 300 years (1419 to 1740).<ref name=Mehta/> Due to security concerns created by [[Pindari|Pindharas]] (nomadic robbers), the fire was temporarily moved to Surat, and as the situation eased it was brought back to Navsari.<ref name=Mehta/> The Sanjan priests and the Bhagarias (local priests) of Navsari had a working arrangement to run the sacred fire temple, but this understanding broke down and legal issues ensued. Disturbed by this development, the Sanjan priests moved out of Navsari with their sacred fire, and housed the fire in one of the two agiaris (the first level of fire temples) in [[Bulsar]] (now known as Valsad), {{Convert|32|km}} away from Navsari. Even here the Sanjan priests could not come to amicable terms with the local priests of the agiari and in 1741 they decided to move to Udvada, which was under the Sanjan community.<ref name=Iranica/><ref name= Hinnells>{{Cite web|last1= Hinnells |first1= John R. |last2= Williams |first2= Alan |url=https://archive.org/stream/ParsisInIndiaAndTheDiaspora/John_Hinnells_Parsis_in_India_and_the_Diaspora_BookFi.org_djvu.txt. |title=Parsis In India And The Diaspora|publisher= I J Routledge , J. Taylor & Francis Group|pp=22,23, 103}}</ref> One year later Zoroastrians built an Atash Behram in Udvada and moved the sacred fire to it;{{Sfn|Hartz|2009|p=61}} it was consecrated by two high priests (dasturs) who had carried the fire from Navsari.<ref name=Mehta/>{{Sfn|Hartz|2009|pp=59&ndash;60}}<ref name= Hinnells/>
The Atash Behram ("Iran Shah fire") is a symbolic representation of the [[Sasanian Empire|Zoroastrian monarchy]] of Iran that was overthrown by [[Arabs]] {{Sfn|Meri|2005|p=877}}), which had been first established at Sanjan in the 90th year of the Yezdezardi era by the first [[Shehenshahi]] Zoroastrian immigrants in India, is now maintained at Udvada by their descendants;{{Sfn|Giara|2002|p=2}} these are nine families of priests who were descendants of the three priests who had retrieved the sacred fire from Sanjan to safety. The presiding High Priest or [[Dastur]] of the temple is chosen by a rotation system among these nine families.<ref name=Iranica/>
To retain the heritage status of the fire temple and the Udvada town, a development plan was initiated in 2007 by the [[Government of India]] and [[Government of Gujarat]] with a fund of [[Indian rupee|Rs.]] 15 million. This involved the preservation of the heritage buildings including the fire temple in Udvada without allowing to make it a tourist hub.<ref name=Sagar/>
==Features== The architect and builder of the temple was Dinshaw Dorabjee Mistry from Mumbai. The temple structure has been built spaciously and well decorated. The main hall of the temple, which is {{Convert|50|x|25|ft}}, is accessed through a two-stage staircase. The flooring in the hall is paved with [[Mintons|Minton tiles]]. A portrait of the [[Zoroaster]] is fixed in the main hall at a vantage position. In the first floor, there is a very large hall of {{Convert|100|x|50|ft}} size. The color scheme, the quality of carpets, and the type of tiles used in the temple have received appreciation from the devotees.{{Sfn|Giara|2002|p=2}} The ''urwisgah'', or place of the rituals for worship, is accessed from the doors on the right at the entrance.{{Sfn|Godrej|Mistree|2002|p=302}} Within this temple, there are the Dasturji Koyaji Mirza hall and a museum.{{Sfn|Rose|2014|p=190}}
In Sanjan, the holy fire was placed in a traditional "altar-like pillar with hollow top" similar to those used in Iran. In Navasari, the fire was kept in an ''āfrinagān'', which was shaped like a vase. A larger version of this was developed as a model for adoption at all other Atash Bahrams.<ref name=Iranica/>
The ''boi'' ritual involves the enthroning of the (machi) of the fire. It is done with ten sticks of [[sandalwood]] of {{Convert|45|cm}} length each; at other similar shrines the number of sandalwood sticks used are seven of {{Convert|30|cm}} length each.{{Sfn|Godrej|Mistree|2002|p=305}}
Portrait of important priests and the religious organizations, who have played a significant role in establishing the temple, are fixed on the outer walls of the temple.{{Sfn|Godrej|Mistree|2002|p=302}} The original temple was refurbished by Lady Motlibhai Wadia in 1894.<ref name= Mulchandani >{{Cite news |last= Mulchandani |first=Anil |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article1350436.ece?service=print |title=Eternal flame of Gujarat |date=30 November 2012 |newspaper=The New Indian Express}}</ref>
==Rituals== The first ''boi'' and ''maachi'', the ceremony that accompanies the regular tending of fire five times a day, was offered to the holy fire at the new temple by Dastur Pheroozi's son.<ref>{{cite book|title=Parsiana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1zwvAAAAYAAJ|year=1996|publisher=P. Warden|page=146}}</ref>
==Pilgrimage== Zoroastrian pilgrims from all parts of India, Canada, Pakistan, and Australia visit the temple on pilgrimage.<ref name=Sagar/> Newly wed couples also visit Udvada on pilgrimage, and on their behalf, their parents offer a ''machi'' (throne of wood to the fire{{Sfn|Kreyenbroek|2013|p=338}}) at the temple.{{Sfn|Kreyenbroek|2013|p=34}}
==Festivals== The anniversary, known as ''sālgiri'', corresponding to the date of establishing the Atash Behram in Udvada and also in other Atash Bahrams in India, is celebrated every year according to the [[Zoroastrian calendar|Shenshai Zoroastrian calendar]] on the day called ''Ādur'' of the month also called ''Ādur'', the ninth Zoroastrian month and the ninth day of the month<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/iransah|title=I Ādur|work=Encyclopedia Iranica}}</ref>); pilgrims visit not only on the day of the month but also throughout the Ādur month.<ref name=Iranica/> Apart from the ''salgiri'', the other religious observance held every month is the "Bahrām" day (the twentieth day of the month). The [[Nowruz|Parsi New Year]], normally held in August, is also celebrated here when a large number of devotees flock to the shrine.<ref name=Sagar/>
On festive occasions, the Udvada shrine comes to life with large number of pilgrims engaged in buying sandalwood, flowers and other religious paraphernalia to offer to the fire.<ref name= Mulchandani/>
